</li>
<li id="cite_note-Harvtxt&#124;Storey&#124;1881-199"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Harvtxt|Storey|1881_199-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Harvtxt|Storey|1881_199-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFStorey1881">Storey (1881)</a></span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-200"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-200">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFWhitmer1888">Whitmer (1888)</a>. <a href="/wiki/Orson_Pratt" title="Orson Pratt">Orson Pratt</a>, who said he had spoken with many witnesses of the plates,(<a href="#CITEREFPratt1859">Pratt 1859</a>, p.&#160;30), assumed that Smith could "break the seal" if only he had been "permitted" (<a href="#CITEREFPratt1877">Pratt 1877</a>, pp.&#160;211–212).</span>
